title: application-gateway-autoscaling-zone-redundant
content:
# Scaling and Zone-redundant Application Gateway v2

This documentation introduces the scaling and zone-redundant features of Azure Application Gateway v2 and WAF v2. There are two modes of scaling: autoscaling and manual scaling.

## Autoscaling
With autoscaling enabled, the Application Gateway and WAF v2 SKUs automatically scale out or in based on application traffic requirements. This mode offers better elasticity to your application and eliminates the need to guess the gateway size or instance count. Autoscaling also allows you to save costs by not requiring the gateway to run at peak-provisioned capacity for expected maximum traffic load.

To enable autoscaling, you must specify a minimum instance count. This ensures that the Application Gateway and WAF v2 don't fall below the specified minimum, even without traffic. Each instance is roughly equivalent to 10 reserved Capacity Units. You can also optionally specify a maximum instance count to limit the scaling. The instance counts can range from 0 to 125, with a default maximum instance count of 10 if not specified.

## Manual Scaling
Alternatively, you can choose manual scaling where the gateway doesn't autoscale. In this mode, you must specify the instance count, which can vary from 1 to 125 instances. If there's more traffic than what the gateway can handle, it could result in traffic loss.

## Autoscaling and High Availability
Azure Application Gateways are always deployed in a highly available fashion. The service is made up of multiple instances that are created based on the configured settings or required by the application load. Even if you configure autoscaling with zero minimum instances, the service is still highly available.

However, creating a new instance can take around six or seven minutes, which can result in downtime. To avoid this, it is recommended to configure a minimum instance count of two, ideally with Availability Zone support. This way, you have at least two instances in your Azure Application Gateway under normal circumstances. If one instance has a problem, the other can handle the traffic while a new instance is being created.

During scale-in events, Application Gateway drains existing connections for 5 minutes on the instance that is being removed. After 5 minutes, existing connections are closed and the instance is removed. Any new connections during or after the 5 minute scale-in time are established to other existing instances on the same gateway.

## Next Steps
- To learn how to schedule autoscaling for Application Gateway, refer to [Schedule autoscaling for Application Gateway](application-gateway-externally-managed-scheduled-autoscaling.md).
- To learn more about Application Gateway v2, refer to [Application Gateway v2 overview](overview-v2.md).
- To create an autoscaling, zone redundant application gateway with a reserved virtual IP address using Azure PowerShell, follow the steps in [Create an autoscaling, zone redundant application gateway with a reserved virtual IP address using Azure PowerShell](tutorial-autoscale-ps.md).

**NOTE:** This document discusses configuration through the Azure Portal. Please _always_ use infrastructure-as-code (IaC) for production environments and deploy through Azure DevOps pipelines.
